nowledge that counts.” It is with this observation that this volume begins, and it continues with a straightforward objective to provide case studies of Pacific kinship. In doing so, contributors share an understanding of kinship as a lived and living dimension of contemporary human lives, in an area where deep historical links provide for close and useful comparison. The ethnographic focus is on transformation and continuity over time in Fiji, Tonga, and Samoa with the addition of three instructive cases from Tokelau, Papua New Guinea, and Taiwan. The book ends with an account of how kinship is constituted in day-to-day ritual and ritualized behavior.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aKinshipzPacific AreavCase studies. 0aKinshipzPacific Area. 0aKinshipzPolynesiavCase studies. 0aKinshipzPolynesia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh1 aBonnemère, Pascale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCayrol, Françoise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouaire-Marsaudon, Françoise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoëm, Ingjerd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHulkenberg, Jara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLin, Ching-Hsiu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNabobo-Baba, Unaisi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPauwels, Simonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPauwels, Simonne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTcherkézoff, Serge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToren, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToren, Chri